\section{Project idea overview}

The idea of this project is to turn a single photo into a walkable 3D environment. A user uploads an image and the program generates a scene so you can walk around, look anywhere, and see parts of the environment that were not visible in the original input image. The goal is a believable and explorable space that feels consistent when changing viewpoints.

Given an input photograph, the program first estimates a dense depth map using Depth Anything V2, which gives per pixel distance information for the overall layout. YOLOv8 detects and segments foreground objects, producing bounding boxes and instance masks. These masks are used to inpaint the occluded background regions with LaMa, giving a cleaner backdrop behind the removed objects. Each segmented object is then lifted into 3D geometry using TripoSR, which produces textured triangle meshes from a single image crop. Using the depth map, the method places the generated 3D assets into a scene using estimated depths, and it estimates object scale from bounding box size relative to distance.

To handle viewpoints that go beyond what the input photo shows, we add a diffusion based generation step during navigation. As the camera moves, we render the current 3D scene, and then use diffusion inpainting conditioned on the rendered view and its depth to synthesize plausible missing content. The newly generated pixels can then be projected back into the scene as updated textures or additional scene points so future renders stay more complete and less smeared. Finally, the composed scene is rendered in the browser using three.js with first person navigation controls, letting the user walk into and explore the reconstructed space.



\section{Literature survey}



WonderWorld by Hong-Xing Yu et al. grows a scene step by step as the camera moves around. Given an input image, the user moves the camera to different viewpoints and adds text prompts to steer how they want that viewpoint to look. The model generates a 2D chunk for that viewpoint and lifts it into a renderable 3D representation with layered Gaussian surfels. This enables the model to predict depth and surfaces norals to allow surfels to be placed efficiently. It also has rules for depth generation overlaps so that stitched areas are less distorted.

Pano Dream by Avinash Paliwal et al.
% approaches the problem uniquely and grows the scene through interaction, where the world is grown step by step as you move the camera. Instead of extending the scene chunk by chunk,
tries to generate a full $360^\circ$ panorama from the single input image. The approach applies diffusion inpainting across overlapping regions in an iterative manner (with optimization) to create a better panoramic blend. Afterwards, it creates a panoramic depth map mirroring the full view, projects the panorama into 3D space, and refines it with Gaussian splatting for new viewpoints to be rendered. The high-level idea is to create a 2D world which is used to create a 3D world.

Depth-Anything-V2 is a monocular depth estimation model that predicts how far each pixel is from the camera using only a single RGB image with no stereo pairs or depth sensors needed. It builds on a DPT (Dense Prediction Transformer) architecture with a DINOv2 vision encoder, trained on a massive dataset of synthetic and real-world images with pseudo-labels. The model outputs a dense relative depth map where each pixel receives a value representing its relative distance, with higher values indicating closer surfaces. It's designed to generalize across diverse scenes without fine-tuning, making it well-suited for turning arbitrary photographs into 3D geometry.

% A Recipe for Generating 3D Worlds From a Single Image by Katja Schwarz et al. has a similar approach for diffusion and 3D lifting technique to the previous two paper's approaches. It also generates a panorama with 2D diffusion inpainting model given the input. Then it estimates metric depth and projects pixels into 3D space as Gaussian splats like Wonderworld. After that, it keeps improving the scene by rendering the current 3D view and using those renders as extra input for inpainting, so it can fill in missing areas more consistently.

pixelNerf by Ben Mildenhall et al. doesn't take a diffusion based approach. Instead of first expanding the scene in 2D and then projecting it into 3D, it predicts a NeRF representation from one or multiple input images using learned image features, and then renders new viewpoints based on that representation. This approach can struggle when large parts of the scene are not visible from the input image, such as regions blocked by occlusions. It can also be slower to render compared to Gaussian based representations, which is why many newer methods prefer using diffusion to fill in unseen content and then convert it into a faster 3D representation for exploration.

\section{Datasets}
Not applicable, as our project will not be requiring datasets. However, this may change as we progress and find the need to use one.


\section{Plan of activities}

% We aim to build a pipeline integrating diffusion view generation, depth estimation, and 3D Gaussian Splatting. Eason will focus on the 2D diffusion and view synthesis, Dan on the depth estimation and point cloud lifting, and Howie on the Gaussian optimization and rendering. We anticipate the 3D reconstruction to be the most challenging component, so we will likely all work together on the final integration.

We aim to build a 3D scene reconstruction pipeline integrating object segmentation, depth estimation, and generative inpainting. Dan will focus on the object segmentation and background completion using YOLOv8 and LaMa. Howie will handle the depth estimation with Depth Anything V2 and the spatial layout logic. Eason will work on the 3D asset generation using TripoSR and the diffusion aspect of the project. We expect the asset generation and diffusion to be the most challenging aspect, so we may collaborate closely on that part.


